    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT a legal requirement?**",
    "text": "There are legal requirements for labelling medicinal products",
    "why": "b) Keep out of reach and sight of children\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nWhile the phrase \"Keep out of reach and sight of children\" is recommended as good practice by the Royal Pharmaceutical Society (RPS) and widely included on dispensed medicines, it is not a legal requirement under the Human Medicines Regulations 2012. Legal labelling requirements for medicinal products are strictly outlined in law and focus on patient safety and traceability.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) Date of dispensing\r\n\r\nThis is a legal requirement to ensure traceability and patient safety. The date of dispensing indicates when the medicine was prepared and supplied, helping with accountability and monitoring medication use.\r\n\r\nc) Name of medicine\r\n\r\nLegally required to identify the product being dispensed. It ensures patients and healthcare providers can accurately determine the specific medication and formulation.\r\n\r\nd) Patient name\r\n\r\nIncluding the patient\u2019s name on the label is a legal requirement to personalise the medicine and prevent confusion or misuse.\r\n\r\ne) Precautions relating to the medical product\r\n\r\nPrecautionary information such as storage conditions or usage warnings (e.g., \"Store below 25\u00b0C\" or \"Take with food\") is legally required to ensure safe and effective use of the medication.\r\n\r\nLabelling of medicinal products is governed by the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 to promote safe and effective use of medicines while ensuring traceability and reducing the risk of misuse. Essential elements that must appear on the label include:\r\n\r\nThe patient\u2019s name for personalisation and accountability.\r\nThe name of the medicine and its strength for clarity.\r\nThe date of dispensing to monitor the timeline of use.\r\nDirections for use to ensure proper administration.\r\nPrecautionary information such as storage conditions or warnings.\r\nWhile \"Keep out of reach and sight of children\" is not a legal requirement, it is a highly recommended practice to further safeguard patients, especially in homes with young children. Pharmacists must ensure compliance with these legal requirements while incorporating best practices to enhance patient safety and adherence.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
