    "why": "(b) AVM - P\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe category AVM - P is not a recognized category of veterinary medicines. Veterinary medicines in the UK are classified into four main categories to regulate their supply, ensuring proper administration and animal safety.\r\n\r\nOther Options Explained:\r\n\r\n(a) AVM - GSL (Authorised Veterinary Medicine - General Sales List): These medicines are available for sale without a prescription and can be purchased by the public without veterinary involvement.\r\n\r\n(c) NFA - VPS (Non-Food Animal - Veterinarian, Pharmacist, Suitably Qualified Person): These medicines are for non-food-producing animals and can be supplied by a veterinarian, pharmacist, or suitably qualified person.\r\n\r\n(d) POM - V (Prescription Only Medicine - Veterinarian): These medicines require a prescription from a veterinarian and are dispensed by a veterinarian or pharmacist.\r\n\r\n(e) POM - VPS (Prescription Only Medicine - Veterinarian, Pharmacist, Suitably Qualified Person): These are prescription medicines for food-producing animals and require a prescription by one of these three qualified professionals.\r\n\r\nThe Veterinary Medicines Regulations (VMR) define these categories to ensure responsible use based on animal type, professional supervision, and public health. Each category has its specific criteria, ranging from medicines available to the general public (AVM - GSL) to those restricted to veterinary prescription (POM - V). The categories support safe supply chains, promote animal welfare, and reduce the risk of misuse in food-producing and companion animals.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
