    "title": "**Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding military prescriptions?**",
    "text": "Small military medical centres can outsource their dispensing to designated community pharmacies.",
    "why": "a) Military prescriptions do not have a designated prescription form\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nMilitary prescriptions do have a designated prescription form known as FMed 296. This form is used by military medical centres and is specific to prescriptions issued within the Ministry of Defence (MOD). The statement that military prescriptions do not have a designated form is therefore incorrect.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\nb) Military prescriptions presented to a non-contracted pharmacy should be treated as private prescriptions\r\n\r\nThis is correct. If a pharmacy does not have a contract with the MOD and is presented with a military prescription (e.g., FMed 296), it must treat the prescription as a private prescription. The patient will pay for the medication and can subsequently claim reimbursement from the MOD.\r\n\r\nc) Non-contracted pharmacies charge the patient for an appropriate fee\r\n\r\nThis is correct. When a military prescription is handled by a non-contracted pharmacy, the pharmacy charges the patient as they would for any private prescription.\r\n\r\nd) Pharmacies with a dispensing contract directly invoice the military of defence\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Pharmacies with a dispensing contract with the MOD are reimbursed directly by the MOD for the prescriptions they dispense.\r\n\r\ne) Prescriptions for Schedule 2 and 3 Controlled Drugs must be written on FP10PCD or equivalent\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Controlled Drugs (CDs) in Schedules 2 and 3 must be written on the appropriate designated form (e.g., FP10PCD or an MOD-equivalent prescription form) to meet legal requirements for dispensing.\r\n\r\n\r\nMilitary prescriptions are issued on the designated FMed 296 form. Military sites often have dispensing doctors, but where this is not available, community pharmacies may be used to dispense medicines.\r\n\r\nContracted pharmacies: Pharmacies with a contract with the MOD invoice the MOD directly for reimbursement.\r\nNon-contracted pharmacies: If the pharmacy does not have a contract, prescriptions should be treated as private prescriptions, and the patient is charged accordingly. The patient can then seek reimbursement from the MOD.\r\nControlled Drugs: Prescriptions for Schedule 2 and 3 Controlled Drugs must comply with the legal requirements for CDs, including being written on an FP10PCD or equivalent designated form.\r\nPharmacists must be aware of these distinctions to ensure compliance with MOD requirements and the Human Medicines Regulations.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
