    "why": "(C) Dispense the medication and make a record in the prescription register.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nGovernment guidelines allow schools to purchase adrenaline auto-injectors (AAIs) without a traditional prescription for emergency use on children who may be at risk of anaphylaxis. A signed order from the school\u2019s head teacher or principal suffices, permitting the pharmacist to dispense the medication under these circumstances.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(A) Advise the nurse to return to the school and get a prescription:\r\nIncorrect. A prescription from a doctor is not necessary; a signed order from the head teacher or principal is adequate.\r\n\r\n(B) Contact the head teacher to discuss the order:\r\nUnnecessary if the signed order complies with legal requirements for supplying AAIs to schools.\r\n\r\n(D) Refuse to dispense the medication as it\u2019s not a prescription from a doctor:\r\nIncorrect. Government regulations permit schools to use a signed order rather than a doctor\u2019s prescription in this case.\r\n\r\n(E) Treat it as a private prescription:\r\nIncorrect. The signed order doesn\u2019t need to be treated as a private prescription. However, an entry should be made in the prescription register for record-keeping.\r\n\r\n\r\nUnder the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidelines, schools in the UK are permitted to purchase AAIs for emergency anaphylaxis treatment based on a signed order from the head teacher or principal. This provision ensures rapid access to life-saving medication, especially for children who may have undiagnosed allergies. The pharmacist can supply the requested AAIs on receipt of a signed order, which must include the product details, quantity, and be authorised by the head teacher. Following the supply, pharmacists must log the transaction in the prescription register to comply with record-keeping requirements, enhancing accountability and ensuring the availability of emergency anaphylaxis treatment in school settings.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson Chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
