    "id": 2507,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding repeatable prescriptions?**",
    "text": "You are teaching pharmacy students about repeatable prescriptions",
    "why": "c) Schedule 3 and 4 Controlled drugs are repeatable on private prescriptions\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nSchedule 3 Controlled Drugs are not repeatable on private prescriptions, as per the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001. However, Schedule 4 (Part I and II) and Schedule 5 Controlled Drugs are repeatable. The distinction between repeatable and non-repeatable Controlled Drugs is vital for pharmacists to ensure compliance with legal requirements.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) If the number of repeats is not stated on a repeatable private prescription then you can dispense it twice\r\n\r\nThis is correct. If a repeatable prescription does not specify the number of repeats, it can be dispensed once initially and once more (total of two dispensings).\r\n\r\nb) Private prescriptions are repeatable\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Private prescriptions can be repeatable unless restricted by the type of medication (e.g., Schedule 2 and 3 Controlled Drugs).\r\n\r\nd) The first dispensing of prescription-only medication and Schedule 5 Controlled drugs must be within 6 months of the appropriate date\r\n\r\nThis is correct. The \"appropriate date\" is either the date the prescription was signed or a later date stated by the prescriber. For most medicines, including Schedule 5 Controlled Drugs, the first dispensing must occur within 6 months.\r\n\r\ne) The first dispensing of Schedule 4 Controlled drugs must be within 28 days of the appropriate date\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Schedule 4 Controlled Drugs (e.g., benzodiazepines) must be dispensed for the first time within 28 days of the appropriate date.\r\n\r\nRepeatable prescriptions allow certain medicines to be dispensed more than once without issuing a new prescription. \r\n\r\nKey points include:\r\n\r\nPrivate prescriptions: These may be repeatable unless they involve Schedule 2 or 3 Controlled Drugs, which are not legally repeatable.\r\nNumber of repeats: If unspecified, prescriptions can be dispensed twice (initial plus one repeat).\r\nControlled Drugs:\r\nSchedule 2 and 3: Not repeatable.\r\nSchedule 4 and 5: Repeatable.\r\nDispensing timelines:\r\nSchedule 4 Controlled Drugs: First dispensing must occur within 28 days.\r\nPrescription-only medicines and Schedule 5: First dispensing must occur within 6 months.\r\nPharmacists must carefully assess prescription details to ensure compliance with legal and ethical standards.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
