    "text": "There has been tighter controls of over the counter medicines containing codeine",
    "why": "d) Pack sizes containing 48 unit doses are licensed as a pharmacy medicine.\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nThe maximum pack size for codeine-containing medicines classified as pharmacy (P) medicines is 32 unit doses. A pack containing 48 unit doses exceeds this limit and would not qualify as a pharmacy medicine. Larger pack sizes are classified as prescription-only medicines (POM) to help mitigate the risks of misuse and dependency associated with codeine.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) Codeine-containing medications are licensed for short-term acute and moderate pain.\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Codeine-containing OTC medicines are indicated for short-term acute moderate pain when alternative pain relief, such as paracetamol or ibuprofen, alone is insufficient.\r\n\r\nb) Codeine-containing medicine is licensed for 3 days' use only.\r\n\r\nThis is correct. The use of codeine-containing medicines is limited to 3 days, and longer use increases the risk of addiction and dependence.\r\n\r\nc) Indications for cold and flu have been removed.\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Licences for OTC codeine have removed indications such as cold and flu symptoms because evidence suggests they do not provide significant relief for these conditions while posing a risk of addiction.\r\n\r\ne) The warning \"Can cause addiction\" must be prominently displayed on the packaging.\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Labelling regulations require all OTC medicines containing codeine to display a clear and prominent addiction warning to inform patients of the risks of misuse.\r\n\r\nCodeine-containing OTC medicines are tightly controlled to reduce the risks of dependency and misuse. These products are only approved for short-term acute moderate pain relief, with a usage limit of 3 days. Indications for less severe conditions like cold and flu have been removed, and the maximum pack size for pharmacy medicines is 32 unit doses. Larger pack sizes are classified as prescription-only medicines. Packaging must include warnings to inform patients about the potential for addiction. Pharmacists are responsible for providing counselling to ensure safe and appropriate use.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
