    "text": "You receive a prescription for a 35- year-old female who has been prescribed isotretinoin for severe acne. You dispensed 20 capsules to the patient on 1st December 2023. Today is the 30th December 2023 and she wishes to collect the remainder of her prescription.\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract of the prescription has been provided for you.\r\nnote: PPP exempt\r\n\r\n![3](https://i.ibb.co/Mk8NsY0/3.png \"400x600\")",
    "why": "(E) The prescription meets all legal requirements therefore dispense the remainder of the prescription.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nSince the prescription includes the note \u201cPPP exempt,\u201d it indicates that the patient is not required to follow the Pregnancy Prevention Programme (PPP), likely because of specific individual circumstances discussed with the prescriber. As a result, the remaining capsules can be dispensed without requiring an additional pregnancy test or new prescription. The prescription meets all necessary legal requirements, and the patient is permitted to collect the remainder of her medication.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\n(A) Advise the patient to return to their GP for a new prescription:\r\nIncorrect. This is unnecessary, as the current prescription remains valid, and the note \"PPP exempt\" indicates the patient is not subject to PPP requirements.\r\n\r\n(B) Contact the GP surgery to specify which brand of isotretinoin is required:\r\nIncorrect. There is no indication in the scenario that the brand needs clarification or has caused issues. Therefore, contacting the GP about brand specification is irrelevant here.\r\n\r\n(C) Provide an emergency supply and request a new prescription from the GP:\r\nIncorrect. An emergency supply is not required because the prescription remains legally valid, and the PPP exemption allows for continued dispensing as directed.\r\n\r\n(D) Request a negative pregnancy test prior to dispensing:\r\nIncorrect. The \u201cPPP exempt\u201d notation on the prescription confirms that the patient does not require a negative pregnancy test prior to dispensing, as she is exempt from PPP requirements.\r\n\r\nIsotretinoin prescriptions for women of childbearing potential are generally subject to the Pregnancy Prevention Programme, which includes monthly pregnancy tests and strict dispensing intervals. However, a prescriber may determine that a patient is exempt from PPP requirements if clinically justified, which should be clearly noted on the prescription (e.g., \"PPP exempt\"). In such cases, as long as the prescription remains valid, the remainder of the medication can be dispensed without additional PPP-related checks, ensuring adherence to patient-specific directives and legal requirements.\r\n\r\nPlease for more information watch the MEP lesson on Chapter 2 (Professional and Legal Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
