    "id": 2488,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which action is the most appropriate?**",
    "text": "Mr L comes into your pharmacy Monday morning with a bag of medicines. He explains that his mum passed away last week and he found some medicine in her house. He asks if he can leave it with you. Upon inspection you notice there are some Fentanyl patches in there.\u00a0\r\n -",
    "why": "E. Make a record in the controlled drug return register, but there is no need for an authorised witness.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nAccording to the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidance, fentanyl patches are Schedule 2 Controlled Drugs (CDs). For patient-returned CDs, the following rules apply:\r\n\r\nA record of the return should be made in a CD return register (not the controlled drug register used for stock).\r\nDestruction of patient-returned CDs does not require an authorised witness but should ideally be carried out in the presence of another member of staff (e.g., another pharmacist or a pharmacy team member) to ensure accountability.\r\nThe patches must be denatured before disposal using an appropriate CD destruction kit to render them irretrievable.\r\nWhy the Other Options Are Incorrect:\r\n\r\nA. Make no record, and there is no need for an authorised witness.\r\nThis is incorrect because the receipt and destruction of returned Schedule 2 CDs must always be recorded in the CD return register to maintain an auditable trail.\r\n\r\nB. Make a record in the controlled drug register and have an authorised witness witness the destruction of the patches.\r\nThis is incorrect because the CD register is only for recording CD stock held in the pharmacy, not patient returns. Additionally, an authorised witness is only required for the destruction of expired pharmacy stock, not for patient-returned CDs.\r\n\r\nC. Make a record in the controlled drug register, but there is no need for an authorised witness.\r\nThis is incorrect because the CD register is not the correct place to record patient returns; the CD return register should be used instead.\r\n\r\nD. Make a record in your prescription register and have an authorised witness witness the destruction of the patches.\r\nThis is incorrect because the prescription register is for recording private prescriptions and supplies of certain CDs, not for the return and destruction of CDs.\r\n\r\nSummary:\r\n\r\nPatient returns of Schedule 2 Controlled Drugs, such as fentanyl patches, must be handled with care to ensure compliance with legal and professional standards. These returns should be recorded in the CD return register, and the medicines must be safely denatured before disposal. While an authorised witness is not required for patient-returned CDs, it is best practice to have another member of staff present during the destruction process to maintain accountability. Following these steps helps to prevent misuse and ensures the secure management of Controlled Drugs.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
