    "text": "Ulipristal and levonorgestrel can sold by pharmacists for emergency hormonal contraception",
    "why": "a) Levonorgestrel is licensed for women over the age of 16 for emergency contraception within 72 hours of unprotected sexual intercourse.\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nLevonorgestrel 1.5mg, when sold over-the-counter (OTC), is licensed for women aged 16 years and above. It is used as an emergency contraceptive within 72 hours (3 days) of unprotected sexual intercourse (UPSI) or contraceptive failure.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\nb) Pharmacists cannot provide advanced emergency hormonal contraception in case of contraceptive failure.\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. Pharmacists can provide advanced supplies of emergency hormonal contraception (EHC) to women under certain circumstances, such as anticipated contraceptive failure. The pharmacist must ensure the patient is competent and will use the medication appropriately.\r\n\r\nc) Ulipristal acetate cannot be sold to those under the age of 16.\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. Ulipristal acetate (EllaOne) can be supplied to patients under 16 years of age, provided the pharmacist assesses the patient for competence under the Fraser guidelines.\r\n\r\nd) Ulipristal acetate for emergency contraception is available as 5mg tablets.\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. Ulipristal acetate (EllaOne) is available as a single 30mg tablet for emergency contraception and must be taken within 120 hours (5 days) of UPSI.\r\n\r\ne) Ulipristal acetate is licensed for those over the age of 16 within 4 days of unprotected sexual intercourse.\r\n\r\nThis is incorrect. Ulipristal acetate (EllaOne) is licensed for use in all reproductive-age women, including those under 16, and is effective for up to 5 days (120 hours) after UPSI.\r\n\r\nPharmacists can supply levonorgestrel and ulipristal acetate for emergency contraception, adhering to specific guidelines:\r\n\r\nLevonorgestrel: Licensed for women aged 16+ for use within 72 hours (3 days) of UPSI.\r\nUlipristal acetate (EllaOne): Licensed for use in all reproductive-age women (including under 16) within 120 hours (5 days) of UPSI.\r\nAdvanced supply: Permissible after assessing patient competency and ensuring appropriate use.\r\nPharmacists must counsel patients on proper use, efficacy timelines, and additional contraception measures to ensure optimal outcomes. \r\nNICE and MEP guidelines stress the importance of accessibility, safety, and patient-centred care.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
