    "title": "**Which of the following is a Schedule 2 Controlled medicine?**",
    "text": "There are different classifications of Controlled drugs",
    "why": "(d) Secobarbital\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nSecobarbital is classified as a Schedule 2 Controlled Drug under the Misuse of Drugs Regulations. While most barbiturates fall under Schedule 3, secobarbital is an exception and is classified as Schedule 2 due to its potential for misuse and dependence. Schedule 2 drugs generally have higher restrictions, including requirements for secure storage, detailed record-keeping, and controlled dispensing protocols.\r\n\r\nOther Options Explained:\r\n\r\n(a) Gabapentin: Gabapentin is a Schedule 3 Controlled Drug. It is not classified as Schedule 2 because its risk profile is generally lower than drugs in Schedule 2.\r\n\r\n(b) Midazolam: Midazolam is classified as Schedule 3, commonly used for short-term sedation, and does not carry the same strict regulations as Schedule 2 drugs.\r\n\r\n(c) Sativex: Sativex, a cannabis-based product, is a Schedule 4 Part 1 Controlled Drug, allowing for its use under specific medical conditions without the tight restrictions of Schedule 2 drugs.\r\n\r\n(e) Temazepam: Temazepam is a Schedule 3 Controlled Drug used primarily for its sedative properties, requiring some controls but not as stringent as those for Schedule 2.\r\n\r\nThe Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guide and NICE guidelines outline the classification of controlled drugs, which helps pharmacists comply with regulations regarding storage, dispensing, and record-keeping. Schedule 2 drugs, like secobarbital, have stricter controls due to their high potential for misuse, necessitating secured storage in a controlled drugs cabinet and logging each transaction in the controlled drugs register. Understanding the classification and associated legal obligations for each schedule ensures safe and compliant handling of controlled substances in pharmacy practice.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
