    "id": 2543,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding controlled drugs requisition?**",
    "text": "Standardised controlled drug requisition forms are a legal requirement for a professional to obtain schedule 1, 2 and 3 controlled drugs.",
    "why": "(c) Faxed controlled drug requisition forms are legally acceptable\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe statement is incorrect because faxed or photocopied requisition forms for controlled drugs are not legally acceptable. For the requisition to be valid, it must be a physical, original document. Accepting faxed or copied requisitions could compromise security and accountability measures surrounding controlled drug distribution.\r\n\r\nOther Options Explained:\r\n\r\n(a) A Home Office license is needed to be in possession of Schedule 1 controlled medicines: This is correct. Possession of Schedule 1 drugs is generally prohibited unless the person has a Home Office license, as these drugs have no recognised therapeutic use in the UK.\r\n\r\n(b) A standardised form is not needed if a hospital pharmacy receives a requisition from a ward within the same legal entity: This is also correct. Hospital pharmacies can receive controlled drug requisitions from wards within the same entity without a standardised form.\r\n\r\n(d) In an emergency, a dentist can be supplied with a Schedule 2 or 3 controlled drug if the requisition will be supplied within 24 hours: This is correct. In an emergency, dentists or doctors can obtain Schedule 2 or 3 drugs if they provide a requisition within 24 hours.\r\n\r\n(e) Pharmacists are not able to requisition Schedule 1 controlled medicines: This is correct. Schedule 1 drugs require a Home Office license for possession, and pharmacists are not authorised to requisition these drugs without one.\r\n\r\nAccording to Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidelines, requisition forms for Schedule 2 and 3 controlled drugs must generally be submitted on a standardised, signed form and must be the original document rather than a faxed or photocopied version. For Schedule 1 drugs, Home Office licensing is necessary, as these drugs have no therapeutic use in the UK. Additionally, emergency provisions allow doctors and dentists to obtain Schedule 2 or 3 controlled drugs immediately, provided they submit a requisition within 24 hours. Pharmacists play a critical role in ensuring that all requisition requirements for controlled drugs are strictly met.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
