    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is the most appropriate action?**",
    "text": "It is a Saturday morning, a 60 year old patient presents to the pharmacy requesting an emergency supply of Clobazam 10mg tablets. He informs he is away from home and he needs medication to prevent nocturnal seizures.",
    "why": "D) Supply 5 days worth of treatment as an emergency supply\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe most appropriate action is to supply 5 days' worth of Clobazam 10mg tablets as an emergency supply. Clobazam, a Schedule 4 Part I controlled drug, is legally allowed to be supplied in an emergency, but only for a maximum of 5 days. This emergency supply ensures the patient can manage his nocturnal seizures temporarily until he can obtain a full prescription.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Advise him it is illegal for you to give controlled medicines as an emergency supply \u2013 This option is incorrect. Although some controlled drugs are restricted in emergency supply situations, Schedule 4 Part I drugs, including Clobazam, can be supplied legally for up to 5 days in an emergency. Advising the patient otherwise would deprive him of needed medication and could increase the risk of seizures.\r\n\r\nB) Refer him to accident and emergency \u2013 This option may not be appropriate in this context. While A&E could provide emergency care, the patient requires ongoing seizure management, which a short-term emergency supply of Clobazam can address without needing to escalate to A&E. Providing the emergency supply within legal limits is more suitable and supports the patient\u2019s need promptly.\r\n\r\nC) Refer him to his general practitioner \u2013 Referring him to his GP may not be feasible on a Saturday, as most GP practices are closed on weekends. Given that an emergency supply of Clobazam is legally allowed, this option is unnecessary and may delay the patient from receiving essential medication.\r\n\r\nE) Supply 28 days worth of treatment \u2013 This option is not appropriate, as it exceeds the legal limit for supplying Schedule 4 Part I drugs as an emergency supply. The law permits a maximum of 5 days' supply, making this option non-compliant and potentially unsafe.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Medicines, Ethics and Practice (MEP) guidelines provide clear instructions on emergency supplies of controlled drugs. Pharmacists may supply certain controlled medicines, such as Schedule 4 Part I drugs like Clobazam, for a maximum of 5 days in an emergency, provided there is an immediate need, such as preventing seizures. This regulation supports continuity of care while upholding legal restrictions to prevent misuse. Referring patients to A&E or GP services should be reserved for situations where an emergency supply is not legally permissible or if the patient\u2019s condition is unstable and requires immediate medical intervention.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
