    "title": "**Which of the following would be the LEAST suitable emergency supply?**",
    "text": "Regulation 225 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 enables patients to request emergency supplies of their medication",
    "why": "E) 28 x Phenobarbital 50mg tablets for epilepsy\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThis answer is least suitable for an emergency supply because Phenobarbital is classified as a Schedule 3 Controlled Drug under the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001. While it is commonly used to treat epilepsy, the maximum quantity that can be supplied for emergency treatment is 5 days' supply, not 28 days. This is due to its controlled status, which limits the quantity available for emergency supply to prevent misuse and to ensure careful monitoring of its use.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) 4 x Zopiclone 7.5mg \u2013 This is a suitable emergency supply in the context of a short-term need for insomnia treatment. Zopiclone is not a controlled drug and can be given in limited quantities for emergency situations, although care should be taken to assess for misuse risks.\r\n\r\nB) 7 x Medroxyprogesterone 5mg tablets \u2013 This is an appropriate emergency supply. Medroxyprogesterone is a hormone used in various therapeutic contexts, and a 7-day supply is reasonable for ensuring continuity of treatment.\r\n\r\nC) 14 x Metformin 500mg tablets \u2013 This is a suitable supply for patients with diabetes. A 14-day supply of Metformin ensures the patient can continue managing their blood sugar levels without interruption while awaiting a full prescription.\r\n\r\nD) 21 x Amlodipine 10mg tablets \u2013 This is a suitable emergency supply. Amlodipine is used for managing hypertension and angina. A 21-day supply is appropriate to maintain ongoing treatment for patients with chronic conditions.\r\n\r\n\r\nUnder Regulation 225 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012, patients can request emergency supplies of their prescribed medication when they have run out and are unable to get a new prescription in time. However, controlled drugs, such as Phenobarbital (a Schedule 3 controlled drug), are subject to stricter regulations. The maximum quantity that can be supplied for emergency treatment is 5 days, reflecting the need for careful monitoring and regulation of controlled substances.\r\n\r\nMedications such as Zopiclone, Medroxyprogesterone, Metformin, and Amlodipine, which are not subject to such strict controls, can be supplied in more appropriate quantities for emergency purposes, depending on the clinical need. Pharmacists must balance the patient's immediate needs with regulatory requirements to ensure patient safety and compliance with the law.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
