    "why": "A. Refuse the sale and advise him he must have a prescription by the veterinary surgeon.\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nThe correct answer is A. Refuse the sale and advise him he must have a prescription by the veterinary surgeon. Under the Veterinary Medicines Regulations 2013, it is illegal to sell human medicines for use in animals unless the product is prescribed by a veterinary surgeon under the veterinary cascade. This regulation ensures that veterinary medicines are used safely and appropriately, as they are specifically formulated for animal use and may differ in strength, formulation, or dosage compared to human medicines.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options\r\n\r\nB. Refuse the sale but advise he can purchase in another pharmacy. \u2013 Incorrect. It is not lawful to advise the customer to purchase the medicine elsewhere. The regulation applies to all pharmacies, not just the one in question.\r\nC. Refuse the sale and request he gets a prescription for his GP. \u2013 Incorrect. A GP prescription would not be appropriate for an animal. Only a veterinary surgeon can prescribe medicines for animals.\r\nD. Say you have not got any in stock. \u2013 Incorrect. This option misrepresents the issue. The problem is not about stock availability but the legal requirement for a veterinary prescription for animal use.\r\nE. Sell chloramphenicol eye drops. \u2013 Incorrect. As mentioned, human medicines cannot be sold for use in animals without a prescription from a veterinary surgeon under the veterinary cascade.\r\n\r\n\r\nUnder the Veterinary Medicines Regulations 2013, it is illegal to sell human medicines, such as chloramphenicol eye drops, for use in animals without a veterinary prescription. These regulations ensure animal welfare and safety, as medications need to be specifically prescribed by a veterinary surgeon, considering the different needs of animals versus humans. Therefore, the correct course of action is to refuse the sale and advise the customer to obtain a prescription from a veterinary surgeon.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
