    "text": "You receive a prescription, on a saturday afternoon for morphine sulfate (zomorph) 10mg capsules, at a dose of one capsule every 12 hours, quantity 120 capsules.",
    "why": "A. Amend the prescription indelibly so the prescription is compliant with the regulations.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nUnder the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001 (as amended), a pharmacist is permitted to make technical amendments to a prescription for Schedule 2 and 3 controlled drugs (e.g., morphine sulfate) in certain situations. The pharmacist can amend the prescription indelibly if:\r\n\r\nEither the quantity in words or the quantity in figures is missing (but not both).\r\nThere are minor typographical errors.\r\nIn this scenario, the prescription does not include the quantity written in words, but it does include the quantity in figures (120 capsules). This means the pharmacist can correct the prescription to comply with the regulations without requiring a new prescription.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA. Amend the prescription indelibly so the prescription is compliant with the regulations\r\n\r\nPharmacists have the authority to amend a Schedule 2 or 3 controlled drug prescription for minor technical details, such as adding the quantity in words. This ensures the prescription complies with legal requirements and allows the pharmacist to supply the medication.\r\n\r\nB. Explain the quantity is not written in words and figures therefore you cannot dispense the prescription\r\n\r\nIf only one of these is missing, the pharmacist can amend the prescription themselves. Refusing to dispense in this case is unnecessary and would cause undue delay for the patient.\r\n\r\nC. Provide 5 days\u2019 worth of medication as an emergency supply\r\n\r\nEmergency supply provisions do not apply to Schedule 2 controlled drugs (except phenobarbital for epilepsy). Morphine sulfate cannot be supplied as an emergency without a valid prescription.\r\n\r\nD. Refer to NHS 111 for a new prescription\r\n\r\nNHS 111 does not issue prescriptions directly; they may arrange out-of-hours GP services. However, this step is unnecessary because the pharmacist can legally amend the prescription.\r\n\r\nE. Refer to the general practitioner for a new prescription\r\n\r\nThis would be an unnecessary delay since the pharmacist is authorised to make technical amendments to the prescription under the law.\r\n\r\nUnder the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001 (as amended):\r\n\r\nA pharmacist can correct technical details, such as the quantity in words or minor errors, on a Schedule 2 or 3 controlled drug prescription, provided it is indelibly amended.\r\nEmergency supply provisions do not apply to Schedule 2 controlled drugs (except phenobarbital for epilepsy).\r\nPrescriptions for controlled drugs must comply with all legal requirements to be valid, but pharmacists can take action to ensure compliance without involving the prescriber unnecessarily.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson Chapter 3 (Underpinning Knowledge : legislation and professional Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
