    "title": "**Which of the following would you NOT be able to supply in instalments?**",
    "text": "A prescriber rings your pharmacy as they are due to start a new service for patients as part of a managed substance withdrawal clinic.\u00a0 He is keen to know what drugs he can prescribe for patients on an instalment basis as part of a withdrawal regimen.",
    "why": "Correct Answer: \r\n\r\nC. Chlordiazepoxide\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nChlordiazepoxide is classified as a Schedule 4 Part I controlled drug (CD4(1)) under the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001.\r\nWhile technically, controlled drugs in Schedule 2, 3, and 4 Part I may be prescribed on an instalment basis, chlordiazepoxide is not suitable for instalment dispensing in clinical practice.\r\nChlordiazepoxide is prescribed for short-course alcohol withdrawal (typically 7\u201310 days) and does not require phased supervised dispensing like methadone or buprenorphine regimens do.\r\nInstalments are mainly used for long-term substance withdrawal programmes to promote compliance and reduce misuse, which does not apply to chlordiazepoxide's short-term use.\r\n\r\nThus, even though chlordiazepoxide is legally a controlled drug, it is not appropriate for instalment prescribing in practice.\r\n\r\nExplanation of other options:\r\n\r\nA. Buprenorphine:\r\n\r\nA Schedule 3 controlled drug widely used in opioid substitution therapy. Instalment prescribing is appropriate and commonly used to promote adherence and prevent diversion or misuse.\r\n\r\nB. Buprenorphine/naloxone combination:\r\n\r\nA Schedule 3 controlled drug used for opioid dependence treatment. Also suitable for instalment prescribing under supervised withdrawal frameworks.\r\n\r\nD. Diazepam:\r\n\r\nA Schedule 4 Part I controlled drug. Diazepam can be prescribed on an instalment basis during supervised withdrawal regimens for benzodiazepine dependence or drug detoxification.\r\n\r\nE. Methadone:\r\n\r\nA Schedule 2 controlled drug and the mainstay of opioid substitution therapy. Instalment dispensing is standard practice to maintain therapeutic levels, improve compliance, and minimise overdose risk.\r\n\r\nUnder the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001 and BNF guidance, instalment prescribing is allowed for controlled drugs in Schedule 2, 3, and 4 Part I, when clinically appropriate.\r\nMedicines like methadone, buprenorphine, buprenorphine/naloxone, and diazepam are commonly dispensed via instalments to support long-term withdrawal management.\r\nAlthough chlordiazepoxide is a Schedule 4 Part I controlled drug, it is not suitable for instalment prescribing because alcohol withdrawal regimens are short-term treatments that do not require phased supervised dispensing.\r\n\r\nPharmacists must ensure instalment prescriptions:\r\n\r\n- Specify the amount per instalment,\r\n\r\n- State the interval between instalments,\r\n\r\n- Use correct legally required wording (e.g., \"Dispense X amount on [specific dates]\").\r\n\r\n- Strict adherence to these requirements supports safe and effective management of withdrawal while remaining fully compliant with legal standards.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
