    "id": 2541,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT an example of home office approved wording?**",
    "text": "The home office has approved specific wording for instalment prescriptions which allows pharmacists a degree of flexibility when supplying either methadone or buprenorphine to a patient.",
    "why": "(a) Consult the prescriber if two or more consecutive days of a prescription have been missed.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe Home Office has established specific, approved wording for instalment prescriptions to provide pharmacists with flexibility when supplying controlled drugs like methadone or buprenorphine. This wording is important for ensuring continuity in patient treatment while also maintaining necessary oversight. One of these approved phrases is \u201cConsult the prescriber if three or more consecutive days of a prescription have been missed.\u201d The option \u201cConsult the prescriber if two or more consecutive days of a prescription have been missed\u201d is incorrect because it does not follow the approved guidance, which specifically states three or more consecutive days.\r\n\r\nOther Options Explained:\r\n\r\n(b) Dispense daily doses in separate containers: This is correct and is an approved phrase to support patient adherence by helping to clarify daily doses.\r\n\r\n(c) If an instalment collection day has been missed, please still dispense the amount due for any remaining day(s) of that instalment: This is correct and is approved wording, allowing for flexibility if a collection is missed.\r\n\r\n(d) Please dispense instalments due on a pharmacy closed days on a prior suitable day: This is correct. This phrase is approved, as it accounts for pharmacy closures and allows for dispensing the instalment early.\r\n\r\n(e) Supervised consumption on collection days: This is correct and approved, indicating that the patient\u2019s dose should be supervised by the pharmacist upon collection.\r\n\r\nThe Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guide emphasises that controlled drug prescriptions for instalments, especially for drugs like methadone and buprenorphine used in opioid dependency, must comply with Home Office-approved wording to maintain safety and continuity in patient treatment. Approved phrases help manage missed doses, reinforce daily adherence, and accommodate pharmacy closures. For missed doses, the guidance specifies consulting the prescriber after three missed days, as missing three consecutive doses could indicate a disruption in the patient\u2019s treatment plan that requires intervention. This level of structure ensures that the pharmacist has clear protocols to follow while still maintaining flexibility to support the patient's needs and safety.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
