    "text": "Miss A, who is visiting the UK from Malta where she was given a private prescription from her family doctor. Miss A presents the prescription to your chemist on 28/04/17 and tells you that she is \u2018scared of flying\u2019 and needs to take the medication prior to her journey home.\r\n\r\nYou contact Miss A\u2019s surgery in Malta and are assured the prescription is genuine. You also confirm that she has no known allergies or any significant medical conditions.\r\n\u00a0\r\n![Screenshot-2024-01-08-at-10-23-17](https://i.ibb.co/C57NqHg/Screenshot-2024-01-08-at-10-23-17.png)",
    "why": "D. You dispense the script and make a record in the prescription register.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nUnder The Human Medicines Regulations 2012, prescriptions written by a doctor from an EEA (European Economic Area) country, such as Malta, are legally valid in the UK, provided they meet all legal requirements. Diazepam is a Schedule 4 Controlled Drug (CD), and while Schedule 4 CDs are subject to specific regulations, they can be prescribed by an EEA healthcare professional.\r\n\r\nFor private prescriptions, a record of the supply must be made in the private prescription register, and all standard prescription requirements must be met, including:\r\n\r\nPatient details (full name, address, and date of birth).\r\nPrescriber details (name, professional address, qualification, and signature).\r\nMedicine details (name, strength, formulation, dose, and quantity).\r\nDate of issue.\r\n\r\nWhy the Other Options Are Incorrect:\r\n\r\nA. You cannot dispense the prescription as it is missing some legal parameters.\r\nThis is incorrect as the scenario does not indicate that the prescription is incomplete. It is stated that the prescription is valid and meets all legal requirements.\r\n\r\nB. You cannot dispense the script as Malta is not in the EEA.\r\nMalta is part of the EEA, and prescriptions from EEA healthcare professionals are legally valid in the UK when requirements are met.\r\n\r\nC. You cannot dispense the script as diazepam is a controlled drug.\r\nDiazepam, a Schedule 4 CD, can be dispensed on an EEA prescription. Unlike Schedule 2 and 3 CDs, it does not require additional CD requisition or register documentation for supply in this scenario.\r\n\r\nE. You dispense the script and make a record in the controlled drugs register.\r\nWhile Schedule 4 CDs like diazepam are controlled, they do not require an entry in the controlled drugs register. A record in the private prescription register is sufficient.\r\n\r\nDiazepam is a Schedule 4 Controlled Drug that can be legally dispensed on an EEA prescription if all requirements are met. The pharmacist must record the supply in the private prescription register, ensuring all details are correctly documented. Unlike Schedule 2 or 3 CDs, there is no requirement for entry in the controlled drugs register or for additional witness procedures. Pharmacists must be diligent in verifying the authenticity of the prescription, especially when issued from another country.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
