    "why": "(d) Morphine sulfate\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nPodiatrists who are independent prescribers have specific restrictions on the controlled medicines they are permitted to prescribe. They are allowed to prescribe certain Schedule 4 and Schedule 5 controlled drugs, but they cannot prescribe Schedule 2 controlled drugs such as morphine sulphate.\r\n\r\nOther Options Explained:\r\n\r\n(a) Diazepam: Podiatrists can prescribe diazepam, a Schedule 4 controlled drug, for appropriate conditions within their prescribing scope.\r\n\r\n(b) Dihydrocodeine: This is a Schedule 5 controlled drug, which podiatrists are authorised to prescribe within their scope of practice.\r\n\r\n(c) Lorazepam: As a Schedule 4 controlled drug, lorazepam can be prescribed by independent prescribers like podiatrists for appropriate cases.\r\n\r\n(e) Temazepam: Temazepam, also a Schedule 3 controlled drug, is within the prescribing authority of podiatrists.\r\n\r\nThe Podiatry Prescribing Regulations allow independent prescribers to prescribe certain controlled medicines, but they cannot prescribe Schedule 2 controlled drugs, which are considered more potent and carry a higher risk of abuse and dependency. Therefore, morphine sulphate is excluded from their prescribing rights due to its classification as a Schedule 2 controlled substance. Podiatrists can prescribe other controlled drugs like dihydrocodeine, diazepam, lorazepam, and temazepam if appropriate for the patient's needs.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
