    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT a requirement of oral retinoids pregnancy prevention programme?**",
    "text": "Pregnancy prevention programmes (PPP)\u00a0 for oral retinoids protect females of a childbearing potential by minimising the risk of becoming pregnant.",
    "why": "E. The maximum quantity for supply is 30 days for oral retinoids under the pregnancy prevention programme.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThe maximum quantity that can be supplied for oral retinoids under the Pregnancy Prevention Programme (PPP) is 30 days, not 28 days. This is to ensure that patients do not receive excessive amounts of medication and to promote ongoing monitoring.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA. Pharmacists can accept emergency supplies at a request of a PPP specialist prescriber:\r\nThis is correct. Emergency supplies for oral retinoids can be accepted if requested by a PPP specialist prescriber, ensuring the patient has access to the medication in urgent situations while still complying with safety protocols.\r\n\r\nB. Pharmacists should not accept repeat prescriptions for oral retinoids:\r\nThis is correct. Repeat prescriptions are not allowed under the PPP for oral retinoids because each prescription must be reviewed to ensure continued compliance with the programme's strict monitoring requirements.\r\n\r\nC. Prescriptions are valid for 7 days:\r\nThis is correct. Prescriptions for oral retinoids under the PPP are only valid for 7 days from the date the prescription is issued. This short timeframe helps ensure the medication is used in close accordance with safety protocols.\r\n\r\nD. Prescriptions should ideally be dispensed on the date prescription is written:\r\nThis is correct. Ideally, prescriptions for oral retinoids should be dispensed as soon as possible after being written to minimise the time a patient is exposed to the potential risks of pregnancy and to ensure compliance with PPP requirements.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Pregnancy Prevention Programme for oral retinoids ensures the safe use of these drugs for females of childbearing potential. The programme has strict requirements to minimise the risk of pregnancy while the patient is using the medication. These requirements include restricting repeat prescriptions, limiting the quantity to 30 days, ensuring prescriptions are dispensed promptly (within 7 days), and requiring ongoing monitoring of the patient's condition and compliance. Emergency supplies are allowed under specific circumstances with an appropriate prescriber request. These guidelines are in place to safeguard both the patient and the unborn child.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
