    "title": "**Which of the following Controlled medicines can be obtained via a midwife supply order?**",
    "text": "Midwives can obtain certain Controlled drugs via midwife supply order",
    "why": "E. Pethidine\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nThe correct answer is E. Pethidine. According to the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidelines, midwives can obtain pethidine, along with diamorphine and morphine, for the purpose of childbirth. These controlled substances are authorised for use in labour and delivery settings to manage pain.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options\r\n\r\nA. Fentanyl \u2013 Fentanyl is not listed as one of the controlled drugs midwives can obtain via a supply order for childbirth.\r\nB. Lorazepam \u2013 Lorazepam is not authorised for midwife supply orders; it is typically used for anxiety or seizures and is not specific to childbirth.\r\nC. Midazolam \u2013 Similar to lorazepam, midazolam is not approved for midwives to obtain via supply orders for childbirth. It is typically used in sedation or anaesthesia.\r\nD. Oxycodone \u2013 Oxycodone is not available through midwife supply orders for childbirth, as its use in this context is not specified.\r\n\r\n\r\nMidwives are authorised to obtain specific controlled drugs through a midwife supply order, but the drugs must be related to childbirth and pain management. Pethidine, diamorphine, and morphine are the approved medications for midwives to use for pain relief during labour. This restriction helps maintain control over the use of high-risk medications while ensuring they are available for critical situations in childbirth.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
