    "id": 2517,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding labelling medicinal products for emergency supplies at the request of a prescriber?**",
    "text": "Regulation 224 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 enables emergencies supplies on the request of a prescriber",
    "why": "E) The words \"emergency supply\"\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nFor emergency supplies at the request of a prescriber, it is not required to label the product with the words \u201cemergency supply.\u201d This label notation is only mandatory for emergency supplies made at the patient's request. Including it for a prescriber request would be incorrect and unnecessary, as the prescriber has authorised the supply directly, which differs procedurally from a patient-initiated request.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Date of dispensing \u2013 This is a required element on the label for all emergency supplies. Recording the dispensing date is essential for tracking the timeline of medication provision and ensuring accurate record-keeping.\r\n\r\nB) Directions for use \u2013 Directions for use must be included to ensure the patient understands how to take the medication correctly. This guidance is crucial for safe and effective treatment adherence, especially in an emergency context.\r\n\r\nC) Name of medicine \u2013 The medicine\u2019s name is necessary on the label to avoid confusion and ensure the patient receives and recognises the correct medication. Proper labelling with the medicine name is a standard requirement for all dispensed medications.\r\n\r\nD) Name of patient \u2013 Including the patient\u2019s name on the label personalises the medication and prevents accidental administration to someone else. This is particularly important for patient safety and compliance.\r\n\r\n\r\nUnder Regulation 224 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012, emergency supplies of prescription-only medicines (POMs) at the request of a prescriber must adhere to specific labelling standards to ensure patient safety and regulatory compliance. When a prescriber requests an emergency supply, the label must include essential details such as the date of dispensing, the medicine name, the patient\u2019s name, and directions for use. These elements promote clear communication and appropriate usage, enabling the patient to manage their treatment safely.\r\n\r\nThe words \u201cemergency supply\u201d are only legally required on labels for emergency supplies requested directly by a patient. Since a prescriber request implies professional oversight and responsibility, this additional notation is not needed. MEP and NICE guidelines reinforce these requirements, supporting pharmacists in delivering accurate, well-labelled medications while maintaining clear distinctions between patient- and prescriber-requested emergency supplies. This framework ensures safe, effective, and regulatory-compliant access to essential medications in urgent situations.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
