    "title": "**Which of the following is NOT a relevant prescriber to authorise emergency supplies?**",
    "text": "Regulation 224 of the human medicines regulations 2012 enables emergencies supplies on the request of a prescriber",
    "why": "B) Doctor from Pakistan\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThis answer is incorrect because a doctor from Pakistan is not an appropriate prescriber to authorise emergency supplies under Regulation 224 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012. The regulation allows emergency supplies to be authorised by prescribers from the UK and EU only. A doctor from outside the EU, such as one from Pakistan, does not meet the criteria for prescribing in the context of emergency supply requests under UK law.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Doctor from France \u2013 A doctor from France is an appropriate prescriber. France is part of the European Union, and under the Human Medicines Regulations 2012, prescribers from EU countries are recognised as authorised to make emergency supply requests in the UK.\r\n\r\nC) UK Nurse Independent Prescriber \u2013 A UK Nurse Independent Prescriber is authorised to make emergency supply requests. Nurse independent prescribers in the UK are able to prescribe certain medications, including in emergency situations, as long as they follow the regulatory requirements.\r\n\r\nD) UK Optometrist Prescriber \u2013 A UK Optometrist Prescriber is also authorised to make emergency supply requests within their scope of practice. Optometrists in the UK, under specific conditions, can prescribe medications and request emergency supplies for patients in need of treatment.\r\n\r\nE) UK Podiatrist Independent Prescriber \u2013 A UK Podiatrist Independent Prescriber is eligible to authorise emergency supplies. As with other independent prescribers in the UK, podiatrists can prescribe and request emergency supplies of medicines within their professional remit.\r\n\r\n\r\nRegulation 224 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 permits emergency supplies to be made at the request of a prescriber, but only those from recognised professional bodies within the UK and the EU are eligible. This ensures that prescribers have the necessary qualifications and are subject to appropriate regulatory oversight to ensure patient safety.\r\n\r\nDoctors, nurse independent prescribers, optometrists, and podiatrists from the UK are authorised to make emergency supply requests for prescription-only medicines (POMs), provided they meet the necessary criteria. However, prescribers from outside the EU, such as those from Pakistan, do not have the authority to request emergency supplies under UK law. This regulatory framework helps maintain patient safety while allowing appropriate access to medications in urgent circumstances.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
