    "id": 2513,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding administration of Anaphylaxis**",
    "text": "Occasionally pharmacists need to administer adrenaline for the treatment of Anaphylaxis",
    "why": "D) Pharmacists require prescriptions for adrenaline prior to administration\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThis answer is incorrect because pharmacists do not require a prescription for adrenaline prior to administration in the case of an emergency such as anaphylaxis. Under the Human Medicines Regulations 2012, pharmacists can administer adrenaline in an emergency situation without the need for a prior prescription. The key requirement is that adrenaline is administered immediately to treat anaphylaxis, a life-threatening condition, which overrides the need for a prescription in urgent cases.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Adrenaline is a prescription-only medicine and is administered intramuscularly \u2013 This is correct. Adrenaline is indeed a prescription-only medicine (POM), and the recommended route of administration for anaphylaxis is intramuscularly (IM), typically into the anterolateral thigh.\r\n\r\nB) Pharmacists need to have training regarding recognising and treating Anaphylaxis \u2013 This is correct. Pharmacists should have appropriate training in recognising and managing anaphylaxis to ensure effective and timely intervention, including the administration of adrenaline when necessary.\r\n\r\nC) Pharmacists providing vaccination services must have access to an Anaphylaxis pack \u2013 This is correct. Pharmacists who provide vaccination services must have access to an anaphylaxis pack, including adrenaline, in case of an allergic reaction following a vaccination.\r\n\r\nE) Pharmacists who administered adrenaline also need to ensure an ambulance is called \u2013 This is correct. Following the administration of adrenaline for anaphylaxis, it is essential that an ambulance is called, as the patient may require further medical treatment and monitoring in a hospital setting.\r\n\r\n\r\nPharmacists are authorised to administer adrenaline in emergency situations such as anaphylaxis without requiring a prescription. The Human Medicines Regulations 2012 allow for the immediate administration of adrenaline in emergencies, particularly for the treatment of severe allergic reactions. Pharmacists must have appropriate training in recognising and managing anaphylaxis and should have access to an anaphylaxis pack when providing services like vaccinations. It is also essential that, after administering adrenaline, an ambulance is called to ensure the patient receives further care and observation. The overall goal is to ensure timely, safe, and effective treatment to prevent life-threatening consequences.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal  issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
