    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**You inform the owner that the prescription can not be supplied, what makes the prescription incomplete about the prescription?**",
    "text": "The following questions relate to a prescription you receive from a pet\u2019s owner. You may find the prescription provided in the resource booklet useful for this question. It must be noted the date of supply is 24.03.17.\r\n\r\nA resource has been provided for this question \r\n\r\n![Screenshot-2024-01-08-at-09-55-55](https://i.ibb.co/Sw3Hb9v/Screenshot-2024-01-08-at-09-55-55.png)",
    "why": "E. The Vet\u2019s registration number is missing, so this must be added.\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nAccording to the Veterinary Medicines Regulations 2013, as amended, a veterinary prescription must include all legally required details to ensure it is valid and compliant. One key legal requirement is the inclusion of the vet\u2019s registration number on prescriptions for Controlled Drugs (CDs), which allows traceability and accountability. If this detail is missing, the prescription is incomplete, and the pharmacy cannot proceed with the supply. The vet must amend and reissue the prescription to include the registration number.\r\n\r\nWhy the Other Options Are Incorrect:\r\n\r\nA. CD statement is incorrect; therefore, it must be taken back to the vet for correction.\r\nThis is incorrect because while CDs require specific statements (e.g., \"for the treatment of an animal under my care\"), there is no indication in this scenario that the CD statement is incorrect.\r\n\r\nB. Supply the prescription to the owner after making sure the dog lives at the address.\r\nThis is incorrect because even if the address is verified, the missing vet registration number renders the prescription invalid, and supply cannot proceed.\r\n\r\nC. The dosing instructions make this unable to supply for an animal.\r\nThis is incorrect. While veterinary prescriptions must have clear dosing instructions, this is not mentioned as an issue in the scenario.\r\n\r\nD. The medicine is not prescribed under the cascade, so that needs to be corrected before the supply is made.\r\nThis is incorrect. The cascade applies to prescribing unauthorised medicines for animals, but there is no suggestion in the scenario that this is relevant to the prescription.\r\n\r\nSummary:\r\n\r\nWhen dispensing veterinary prescriptions, it is essential to ensure compliance with the Veterinary Medicines Regulations 2013. For Controlled Drugs (CDs), the vet\u2019s registration number must be included on the prescription, among other legal requirements. If any mandatory detail is missing, the prescription cannot be supplied, and the issue must be corrected by the prescribing vet. Always verify veterinary prescriptions carefully to ensure they meet all legal and professional standards before supply.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
