    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which one of the following is NOT a legal requirement for recording the receipt/supply of controlled medicines?**",
    "text": "Schedule 2 controlled drugs need to be entered in to the Controlled Drugs register once received or supplied in the pharmacy",
    "why": "Correct Answer: \r\n\r\nE) Whether ID was requested\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\n- The Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001 and Home Office guidance outline the legal requirements for entries in the Controlled Drugs Register (CDR) when receiving or supplying Schedule 2 controlled drugs.\r\n\r\n- While good practice encourages some additional entries (like running balances or checking ID), only specific fields are legally mandatory.\r\n\r\n- \"Whether ID was requested\" is not one of the legal requirements and is therefore the correct answer to this question.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Date of supply - required\r\n\r\nLegally must be recorded to document when the controlled drug was supplied or received.\r\n\r\nB) Patient address \u2013 required\r\n\r\nFor supplies, the address of the person receiving the controlled drug must be entered.\r\n\r\nC) Patient name \u2013 required\r\n\r\nEssential for identifying the recipient and ensuring traceability.\r\n\r\nD) Running balance of controlled medicine \u2013  Not legally required, but strongly recommended\r\n\r\nAlthough not mandatory by law, the running balance is considered best practice (as per NICE, CQC, GPhC) to enhance accountability and safety.\r\n\r\nE) Whether ID was requested \u2013 Not required\r\n\r\nThere is no legal requirement to record whether or not ID was requested or verified. Though advisable in certain cases (e.g. when someone unknown is collecting), it does not need to be documented in the register.\r\n\r\n\r\n- The Controlled Drugs Register is a legal document used to record the receipt and supply of Schedule 2 controlled drugs.\r\n\r\n- According to the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001, the mandatory legal entries include:\r\n\r\n- Date of transaction (supply or receipt)\r\n\r\n- Name and address of the patient (for supply)\r\n\r\n- Details of the person or supplier received from (for receipt)\r\n\r\n- Quantity supplied or received\r\n\r\n- Form and strength of the controlled drug\r\n\r\n- Name of the prescriber (if applicable)\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
