    "id": 2505,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following does not meet legal requirements of a prescription?**",
    "text": "Regulation 217 of the human medicines regulations states the legal requirements for prescriptions",
    "why": "c) Copies of electronic prescriptions can be sent via email\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nUnder Regulation 217 of the Human Medicines Regulations, copies of electronic prescriptions cannot be legally sent via email as they are not considered valid. Electronic prescriptions must be securely transmitted via the NHS Spine to a nominated pharmacy, ensuring a secure and authorised transfer of the prescription. Sending them via email is not a legally recognised or secure method of transmission.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) Advanced electronic signatures that are uniquely linked to a signatory is acceptable for NHS electronic prescriptions\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Advanced electronic signatures that are securely linked to a signatory are acceptable for NHS electronic prescriptions, as they ensure authenticity and accountability.\r\n\r\nb) Carbon copies of prescriptions are permissible as long as they are signed in ink\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Carbon copies of prescriptions are legally valid once they are signed in indelible ink, ensuring the authenticity of the prescription.\r\n\r\nd) Prescription can be computer generated or typed\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Computer-generated or typed prescriptions are legally valid, provided they meet all other legal requirements (e.g., appropriate signatures and necessary details).\r\n\r\ne) Prescriptions need to be written in indelible ink\r\n\r\nThis is correct. Prescriptions must be written in indelible ink or computer-generated, ensuring the prescription cannot be altered after it is written.\r\n\r\nRegulation 217 outlines the legal requirements for prescriptions, ensuring they are authentic, secure, and legally valid. Key points include:\r\n\r\nElectronic prescriptions: Must be transmitted securely via the NHS Spine and cannot be sent via email.\r\nSignature requirements: Advanced electronic signatures and physical signatures in indelible ink are valid for prescriptions.\r\nCarbon copies: Carbon copies are permissible as long as they are signed in indelible ink to ensure authenticity.\r\nPrescription format: Prescriptions can be computer-generated or typed, provided they meet all other requirements.\r\nIndelible ink: Prescriptions must be written in indelible ink, ensuring that they cannot be altered after being written.\r\nBy adhering to these guidelines, pharmacies ensure prescriptions are legally valid, secure, and compliant with relevant regulations.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
