    "text": "Midwives can obtain certain Controlled drugs via midwife supply order",
    "why": "D. Signature of midwife\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nThe correct answer is Signature of midwife. A midwife supply order does not require the signature of the midwife. Instead, the order must include the signature of the appropriate medical officer\u2014either a doctor authorised by the local supervising authority or an appointee of a person with such authority. This signature requirement ensures proper authorisation and accountability for controlled drug supply.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options\r\n\r\nA. Name of midwife \u2013 Legally required, as it identifies the midwife requesting the controlled drugs.\r\nB. Occupation of midwife \u2013 Required to verify the professional status of the requestor as a midwife.\r\nC. Purpose of midwife supply order \u2013 Necessary to specify the intended use for the controlled drugs.\r\nE. Total quantity of drug to be obtained \u2013 Required to indicate the exact amount of controlled drugs to be supplied.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guidelines, midwife supply orders for controlled drugs must be properly documented and authorised. The legal requirements ensure appropriate control and minimise misuse by specifying key details like the midwife\u2019s name, occupation, purpose, and total quantity needed. However, the midwife\u2019s signature is not required; the authorisation signature must come from a designated medical officer. This system upholds both accountability and safety in the handling of controlled substances.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 2 (Professional and legal issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
