    "id": 2516,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following is INCORRECT relating to emergency supplies at the request of the prescriber?**",
    "text": "Regulation 224 of the human medicines regulations 2012 enables emergencies supplies on the request of a prescriber",
    "why": "B) Maximum of 30 days supply of medication\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThis statement is incorrect. The maximum supply of medication for an emergency supply at the request of a prescriber does not have a set limit of 30 days. Unlike emergency supplies requested by a patient, which are limited to a maximum of 30 days, emergency supplies requested by a prescriber are not subject to such a restriction. The amount of medication supplied is determined based on the clinical need and the prescriber\u2019s directions.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) Entry must be made in the POM register \u2013 This is a correct requirement. When an emergency supply is made, an entry must be recorded in the Prescription-Only Medicines (POM) register, which ensures proper tracking and documentation of the supply in compliance with regulatory standards.\r\n\r\nC) Medicine is supplied in accordance to prescriber directions \u2013 This is accurate. The medicine supplied under an emergency supply request from a prescriber must be given in accordance with the directions provided by the prescriber, ensuring the treatment aligns with the intended clinical management.\r\n\r\nD) Prescription must be provided within 72 hours \u2013 This is a correct condition. For an emergency supply at the request of a prescriber, the patient must obtain a full prescription within 72 hours. This ensures that the emergency supply is only a temporary solution until the proper prescription is issued.\r\n\r\nE) Schedule 2 Controlled drugs cannot be supplied \u2013 This is accurate. Schedule 2 controlled drugs cannot be supplied as an emergency supply under Regulation 224. These medications are subject to strict controls, and their supply must be managed according to additional regulations that prevent emergency provision.\r\n\r\nRegulation 224 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012 outlines the provisions for emergency supplies made at the request of a prescriber. This regulation allows pharmacists to provide an emergency supply of medication to patients when a prescriber requests it, provided that specific conditions are met.\r\n\r\nThe key requirements include that the supply must be recorded in the POM register, and the medicine must be dispensed according to the prescriber\u2019s instructions. For Schedule 2 controlled drugs, emergency supplies cannot be made, ensuring strict control over these substances. Additionally, the patient must obtain a prescription within 72 hours of receiving the emergency supply.\r\n\r\nImportantly, unlike patient-requested emergency supplies, which are limited to a 30-day supply, there is no maximum supply period for emergency supplies requested by a prescriber. This distinction helps ensure that patients receive the necessary amount of medication based on their individual needs, as determined by the prescriber, while also maintaining compliance with legal and regulatory frameworks designed to ensure patient safety.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
