    "id": 2529,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**What is the maximum number of days you can supply?**",
    "text": "A 32 year old male patient presents to your pharmacy explaining he is away from home and requires an emergency supply of co-codamol 30/500mg tablets.. After checking the Summary Care Record, you determine the request is valid.",
    "why": "B) 5 days\r\n\r\nRationale: \r\n\r\nWhen supplying a controlled drug (CD) under an emergency supply, the maximum quantity that can be provided is dependent on the schedule of the medication and the specific legal requirements set out in the Human Medicines Regulations 2012, as amended. For Schedule 5 controlled drugs, such as co-codamol 30/500mg (which contains codeine phosphate), you can only provide a maximum of 5 days' worth of treatment under an emergency supply.\r\n\r\nEmergency supply regulations (Regulation 225) dictate that, for Schedule 5 CDs, the quantity supplied should be no more than a 5-day supply. If a patient requires more than 5 days' worth, they must have a prescription issued from a registered prescriber.\r\nOther Options:\r\n\r\nA) 3 days: This is not correct as the maximum supply for a Schedule 5 controlled drug is 5 days, not 3 days. A 3-day supply could apply to other medications or different emergency supply situations, but not for Schedule 5 controlled drugs.\r\n\r\nC) 7 days: This is incorrect. A 7-day supply could be applicable for some medications, such as non-controlled drugs under emergency supply regulations, but for Schedule 5 controlled drugs, the limit is 5 days.\r\n\r\nD) 28 days: This is not appropriate for controlled drugs. A 28-day supply is typically seen for other prescriptions like regular, non-controlled medications or repeat prescriptions, but controlled drugs like co-codamol 30/500mg are strictly regulated.\r\n\r\nE) 30 days: Similarly, a 30-day supply is far beyond the legal limit for controlled drugs under emergency supply provisions, especially for Schedule 5 drugs. This would be more appropriate for chronic conditions but not for controlled drugs like co-codamol.\r\n\r\nUnder Regulation 225 of the Human Medicines Regulations 2012, the maximum supply for a Schedule 5 controlled drug, such as co-codamol 30/500mg, can only be up to 5 days in an emergency situation. This regulation ensures that while emergency supplies can be made to prevent harm to the patient, there is a limit on how much controlled substance can be dispensed without a prescription. Beyond 5 days, a prescription is required to comply with legal standards and patient safety.\r\n\r\nThis guideline is essential for pharmacy practice to ensure that controlled drugs are handled appropriately and within the constraints of the law, safeguarding both the patient and the pharmacy.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
