    "title": "**Which of the following medicines would have a validity of 6 months after the appropriate date on a prescription?**",
    "text": "Some Controlled medicines have shorter validity on prescriptions",
    "why": "(c) Oramorph 10mg/5mL oral suspension\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nOramorph 10mg/5mL oral suspension is classified as a Schedule 5 Controlled Drug. Prescriptions for Schedule 5 drugs have a validity of 6 months from the appropriate date on the prescription. This longer validity period is due to the lower potential for abuse and dependence associated with Schedule 5 drugs, compared to those in Schedules 2, 3, and 4, which have a stricter 28-day validity.\r\n\r\nOther Options Explained:\r\n\r\n(a) Clenbutarol: Not a controlled drug, but it would generally follow standard prescription validity rules, typically 6 months unless otherwise specified.\r\n\r\n(b) Methadone: Methadone is a Schedule 2 Controlled Drug, which requires prescriptions to be dispensed within 28 days of the appropriate date.\r\n\r\n(d) Oxycodone: Oxycodone is also a Schedule 2 Controlled Drug, requiring dispensing within 28 days.\r\n\r\n(e) Pregabalin: Pregabalin is a Schedule 3 Controlled Drug with a prescription validity of 28 days.\r\n\r\nIn the UK, the Medicines, Ethics, and Practice (MEP) guide and NICE guidelines outline specific validity periods for different schedules of controlled drugs. Schedule 5 drugs, such as low-strength morphine preparations (e.g., Oramorph 10mg/5mL oral suspension), have reduced regulatory controls due to their lower abuse potential, allowing prescriptions to be valid for 6 months. Higher schedules (Schedules 2, 3, and certain Schedule 4 drugs) are subject to tighter controls, including the shorter 28-day prescription validity.\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 3 (Underpinning knowledge: legislation and professional issues)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
