    "id": 2549,
    "bank": "clinicalMep",
    "title": "**Which of the following makes the prescription legally not valid?\u00a0**",
    "text": "You receive a prescription for sevredol (morphine sulfate) 10mg tablets for a palliative care patient\u00a0\r\n\r\nHowever you realise you cannot dispense the prescription\u00a0\r\n\r\nAn extract of the prescription has been provided for you\u00a0\r\n![mepRxs-2](https://i.ibb.co/khcSv3Y/mepRxs-2.png)",
    "why": "Correct Answer: \r\n\r\nB) The dose is not legally suitable\r\n\r\nRationale:\r\n\r\nThis is a Schedule 2 Controlled Drug (morphine sulfate), and under Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001 and MEP, the prescription must include a clear and unambiguous dose.\r\n\r\nThe phrase:\r\n\r\n\u201cTake every 4\u20136 hours when required\u201d\r\n\r\ndoes not specify the actual dose, such as \"Take 1 tablet every 4\u20136 hours when required\".\r\nWithout the specific number of tablets or quantity to take, the dose is not legally valid and cannot be dispensed.\r\n\r\nExplanation of Other Options:\r\n\r\nA) A nurse independent prescriber cannot prescribe Sevredol\r\n\r\nIncorrect \u2013 Nurse Independent Prescribers can prescribe Schedule 2 controlled drugs, including morphine sulfate, provided it is within their clinical competence and for legitimate medical need, such as palliative care (MEP Chapter 2).\r\n\r\nC) The prescription has expired\r\n\r\nIncorrect \u2013 Controlled Drug prescriptions are valid for 28 days from the date on the prescription. This prescription is marked \u201cTODAY'S DATE\u201d so it is still within the valid timeframe.\r\n\r\nD) The quantity is not written in words and figures\r\n\r\nIncorrect \u2013 In the extract, the quantity is written as:\r\n\r\n\u201cQuantity: 56 (fifty six)\u201d\r\nThis meets the legal requirement for Controlled Drugs, where the quantity must be written in both words and figures to prevent tampering.\r\n\r\nE) The prescription needs to be on a standardised form\r\n\r\nIncorrect \u2013 This is a standard FP10 prescription used in England by independent prescribers such as GPs, NIPs, and others.\r\n\r\nControlled drug prescriptions must meet certain legal wording and content requirements (e.g. dose, quantity, form, strength), but they do not need to be on a special or different form unless issued in specific settings (e.g. private prescriptions for Schedule 2/3 CDs must be on FP10PCD in England).\r\n\r\nIn this case, since it is an NHS prescription from a nurse independent prescriber, and not a private prescription, it does not need a different standardised form beyond the usual controlled drug legal content requirements.\r\n\r\nControlled Drug Prescription Requirements (MEP & Legal Framework):\r\n\r\n- Under MEP Chapter 2 and Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001, a Schedule 2 Controlled Drug prescription must include:\r\n\r\n- The form and strength of the medicine\r\n\r\n- Clear dose (e.g. \"Take 1 tablet every 4\u20136 hours\")\r\n\r\n- Total quantity in words and figures\r\n\r\n- Valid prescriber details and signature\r\n\r\n- Dated within the last 28 days\r\n\r\n- Prescriptions lacking any of these legal requirements (especially an unambiguous dose) are not valid and must not be dispensed.\r\n\r\n\r\nPlease for more information watch the MEP lesson on Chapter 2 (Professional and Legal Issues):\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
