    "title": "**Which of the following medications must be prescribed on a standardised form?**",
    "text": "You are the responsible pharmacist in your community pharmacy and you teaching your trainee pharmacists about private controlled drug prescriptions",
    "why": "e) Tramadol\r\n\r\nRationale\r\n\r\nPrivate prescriptions for Schedule 2 and 3 Controlled Drugs must be written on a standardised private prescription form (e.g. FP10PCD in England). Tramadol is classified as a Schedule 3 Controlled Drug, and as such, it must adhere to this legal requirement.\r\n\r\nExplanation of the Other Options\r\n\r\na) Clenbuterol\r\n\r\nClenbuterol is not a controlled drug in the UK. It is a prescription-only medicine (POM), and POMs do not require a standardised form.\r\n\r\nb) Diazepam\r\n\r\nDiazepam is a Schedule 4 (Part I) Controlled Drug. Schedule 4 drugs do not require a standardised private prescription form.\r\n\r\nc) Lorazepam\r\n\r\nLike diazepam, lorazepam is also a Schedule 4 (Part I) Controlled Drug, and therefore a standardised form is not needed.\r\n\r\nd) Sativex\r\n\r\nSativex is a Schedule 4 (Part I) Controlled Drug, which does not require a standardised private prescription form.\r\n\r\ne) Tramadol\r\n\r\nTramadol is a Schedule 3 Controlled Drug and must be prescribed on a standardised private prescription form, such as FP10PCD in England.\r\n\r\nKey Points About Controlled Drug Prescriptions\r\n\r\nSchedule 2 and 3 Controlled Drugs:\r\n\r\nMust be prescribed on a standardised private prescription form (e.g. FP10PCD in England).\r\nExamples include tramadol (Schedule 3) and morphine (Schedule 2).\r\n\r\nSchedule 4 and 5 Controlled Drugs:\r\n\r\nThese do not require a standardised form for private prescriptions.\r\nExamples include diazepam, lorazepam, and Sativex.\r\n\r\nMisuse of Drugs Regulations 2001:\r\n\r\nEstablishes the classification of controlled drugs into Schedules 1\u20135.\r\n\r\nSummary\r\n\r\nIn the UK, private prescriptions for controlled drugs must comply with legal requirements established under the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001. A standardised private prescription form (e.g. FP10PCD in England) is mandatory for Schedule 2 and 3 Controlled Drugs, including tramadol, to ensure proper documentation and reduce misuse. In contrast, Schedule 4 and 5 Controlled Drugs\u2014such as diazepam, lorazepam, and Sativex\u2014are exempt from this requirement. Pharmacists must verify that prescriptions for controlled drugs meet all legal requirements to maintain compliance and safeguard patient safety. For detailed guidance, refer to MEP Chapter 4.\r\n\r\n\r\nFor more information watch MEP lesson chapter 4 (The Responsible Pharmacist)\r\n\r\nhttps://preregshortcuts.com/courses/medicines-ethics-practice-course-mep",
